PART B — LOGIC CORRECTNESS STANDARD

10. LOGIC FIRST, CODE SECOND

Before coding, resolve:

What is the input?
What is the output?
What can fail?
What is the expected state transition?
What should happen on empty/null/invalid data?
What should happen on slow network?
What should happen on repeated submit?

Do not write UI that looks good but has fragile logic.


---

11. DATA FLOW MUST BE CLEAR

For every feature:

User Action → Validation → Processing → State Update → UI Feedback → Error Handling

Rules:

Validate before processing

Do not trust client data

Keep data shape consistent

Avoid hidden global mutation

Avoid duplicated source of truth

Avoid state that can go stale

Avoid race condition on async flow

Disable submit while processing

Handle empty, loading, success, and error states



---

12. TYPES & VALIDATION

TypeScript:

Avoid any

Avoid non-null assertion ! unless truly safe

Use explicit return type for exported/public functions

Use Zod or schema validation for external data

Parse unknown API response before using it


Bad:

const data: any = await res.json()
return data.user.name

Good:

const raw = await res.json()
const parsed = userResponseSchema.safeParse(raw)

if (!parsed.success) {
  throw new Error("Invalid API response")
}

return parsed.data.user.name


---

13. ERROR HANDLING

Every async operation must handle failure.

Required:

User-friendly error message

Internal error not exposed

Retry option when useful

Loading state

No silent fail

No unhandled promise

No raw stack trace to user


Error hierarchy:

Input Error       → user can fix
Auth Error        → user needs login/permission
Business Error    → action rejected by rules
Network Error     → retry possible
Server Error      → generic user message + internal log


---

