PART C — SECURITY STANDARD

16. SECURITY BY DEFAULT

Every generated code must be secure by default.

Rules:

Never hardcode secrets

Never expose API keys in frontend

Never trust client input

Never return raw stack traces

Never concatenate SQL strings

Never render unsanitized HTML

Never store sensitive token in unsafe place

Never log secrets

Never use weak default secret


Use env vars:

const apiKey = process.env.API_KEY

if (!apiKey) {
  throw new Error("Missing API_KEY environment variable")
}


---

17. INPUT SECURITY

All user input must be validated.

Validate:

type
format
length
range
allowed values
file size
file MIME type
ownership/permission

For API routes:

Reject invalid input early

Use 400/422 for validation errors

Use 401 for unauthenticated

Use 403 for unauthorized

Use 429 for rate limit

Use 500 only for unexpected server error



---

18. AUTH & PERMISSION

Never check only “is logged in” if ownership matters.

Required logic:

Is user authenticated?
Does user own this resource?
Does user have permission for this action?
Is the resource still valid?

Bad:

await db.project.delete({ where: { id } })

Good:

await db.project.delete({
  where: {
    id,
    ownerId: session.user.id
  }
})


---

19. API SECURITY

For public endpoints:

Rate limit

Validate request body

Validate method

Reject oversized payload

Use consistent response envelope

Do not leak internal error

Add CORS only when needed

Avoid wildcard CORS with credentials

Use CSRF protection for cookie-based auth mutations


Default response shape:

{
  "success": true,
  "data": {},
  "error": null,
  "meta": {}
}

Error response:

{
  "success": false,
  "data": null,
  "error": {
    "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
    "message": "Invalid input"
  },
  "meta": {}
}


---

20. FRONTEND SECURITY

Rules:

Do not put secrets in NEXT_PUBLIC_*

Do not dangerously set HTML unless sanitized

Do not trust hidden inputs

Do not trust disabled fields

Do not expose admin-only UI logic as security boundary

Mask sensitive values

Clear sensitive state after use when relevant

Avoid storing JWT in localStorage if cookie-based auth is possible


If using external links:

<a href="https://example.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
  Open
</a>


---

21. DEPENDENCY SECURITY

Before adding dependency:

Is it necessary?
Can native API solve this?
Is it maintained?
Is it too large?
Does it run on client unnecessarily?
Does it introduce supply-chain risk?

Rules:

Avoid dependency for simple utility

Prefer well-maintained packages

Do not add heavy animation library for tiny animation

Do not add UI framework if existing styling is enough

Pin important backend/security dependencies when relevant



